  ],
  "theory": "Star-to-Delta (Y-Δ) transformation allows us to convert a three-terminal star (Y) network into an equivalent delta (Δ) network. In a star circuit, three impedances meet at a common neutral point N. In the equivalent delta circuit, three impedances connect directly between the three terminals A, B, C. The conversion formulas are: RAB = (RA·RB + RB·RC + RC·RA)/RC, RBC = (RA·RB + RB·RC + RC·RA)/RA, RCA = (RA·RB + RB·RC + RC·RA)/RB. This transformation is used to simplify complex networks that cannot be reduced by series-parallel combinations alone.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "Star (Y): three impedances connected to a common neutral point N",
    "Delta (Δ): three impedances connected between three terminals (no neutral)",
    "Each delta resistance = sum of products of adjacent star resistors / opposite star resistor",
    "Inverse: Delta-to-Star: RA = RAB·RCA/(RAB+RBC+RCA)",
    "Used to simplify bridge circuits and three-phase network analysis"
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Three-phase power system analysis (Δ↔Y load conversion)",
    "Simplifying bridge circuit networks (Wheatstone bridge)",
    "AC circuit analysis where series-parallel rules don't apply"
  ]
}
